<paragraph blockId="13.[138,251,859,883]" box="[138,251,859,883]" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381">
<emphasis box="[138,251,859,883]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381">Etymology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[138,759,908,932]" box="[138,759,908,932]" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381">
Named for its resemblance to 
<taxonomicName authority="Lundblad." authorityName="Lundblad." box="[495,759,908,932]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laceratus">
<emphasis box="[495,629,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381">H. laceratus</emphasis>
Lundblad.
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[138,233,989,1013]" box="[138,233,989,1013]" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381">
<emphasis box="[138,233,989,1013]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="13.[138,1185,1037,1255]" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381">
The species is very similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[481,614,1037,1061]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laceratus">
<emphasis box="[481,614,1037,1061]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381">H. laceratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs in the shape and configuration of the acetabula. The acetabula are small in 
<taxonomicName authority="Smit, 2005" authorityName="Smit" authorityYear="2005" box="[590,753,1070,1094]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laceratoides" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[590,753,1070,1094]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381">H. laceratoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[763,860,1070,1094]" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, and large (38 long and 24 wide) in 
<taxonomicName box="[248,385,1102,1126]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laceratus">
<emphasis box="[248,385,1102,1126]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381">H. laceratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The acetabula are placed in a line behind each other in the new species, while they are arranged in a triangle in 
<taxonomicName box="[676,803,1134,1158]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laceratus">
<emphasis box="[676,803,1134,1158]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381">H. laceratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The palps of the two species are similar. K. O. 
<bibRefCitation author="Viets KO" box="[318,462,1166,1190]" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381" pagination="467 - 485" refId="ref11940" refString="Viets KO. 1963. Hygrobatidae (Acari, Hydrachnellae) aus Sudafrika. Archiv fur Hydrobiologie 59: 467 - 485." type="journal article" year="1963">Viets (1963)</bibRefCitation>
described another similar species from 
<collectingCountry box="[940,1091,1166,1190]" name="South Africa" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381">South Africa</collectingCountry>
, i.e. 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sudafricanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381">H. sudafricanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This species differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Smit, 2005" authorityName="Smit" authorityYear="2005" box="[571,726,1199,1223]" class="Arachnida" family="Hygrobatidae" genus="Hygrobates" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laceratoides" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[571,726,1199,1223]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381">H. laceratoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[736,826,1199,1223]" pageId="13" pageNumber="3381" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in having PII almost without a ventral extension, I-leg-5 distally with two blunt setae and the acetabula are arranged in a triangle.
</paragraph>
